    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="114"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <head>114. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d114fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 710, Country Files, Europe,
                            <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>, Vol. VI. Secret. Sent for
                        information. Although no drafting information appears on the memorandum,
                            <persName corresp="#p_LLE1">Lynn</persName> sent it to <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> under a December 24 covering
                        memorandum. <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> wrote the following
                        comments in the margins: “This doesn’t make my point—what about tests of <hi
                            rend="italic">new</hi> weapons? How many new weapons have they developed
                        in 5 years compared with us? 2) <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >K[issinger]</persName>—also, I want a study made of the point I
                        discussed with you re. How Soviet gets so much more for their 70 billion a
                        year than we do.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-12-30">December 30, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>SUBJECT <list>
                            <item>Number of Soviet and <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Missile
                                Tests</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>You asked for information about the number of Soviet and <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> missile tests in 1969.</p>
                <p>In 1969, the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> conducted 104 tests of
                    operational missiles; the Soviets, 108.</p>
                <list>
                    <item>—This was a slight decrease for the Soviets from their 1968 level of 119,
                        and a substantial increase for the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>,
                        which ran 78 missile flights in 1968.</item>
                    <pb facs="0426" n="397" xml:id="pg_397"/>
                    <item>The major reason for the decrease in Soviet tests was a sharp decline in
                        troop training firings of their older SS–7 and SS–8 <gloss target="#t_ICBM1"
                            >ICBM</gloss>s.</item>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> increased testing is accounted for
                        equally by an increase in firings of operational missiles for training and
                        confidence, and an increase in <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss>
                        flights.</item>
                    <item>—80 of the Soviet tests, as against 57 of the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >U.S.</gloss>, were of land-based <gloss target="#t_ICBM1"
                        >ICBM</gloss>s.</item>
                    <item>—Almost half the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> flights (47 of 104)
                        were of submarine missiles. Reflecting their fewer operational ballistic
                        missile subs, they ran only 28 <gloss target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss>
                        tests.</item>
                    <item>—Both countries made substantial increases in the number of tests
                        associated with research and development rather than training and confidence
                        testing of operational systems: <list>
                            <item>—The Soviets made 21 <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss>
                                flights, compared with 13 the year before.</item>
                            <item>—40 of the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> flights were <gloss
                                    target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss>-associated, compared with 25 the
                                year before.</item>
                            <item>—Most of the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>
                                <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss> flights were connected with
                                the well-advanced Minuteman III and Poseidon programs; the Soviet
                                    <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss> flights include two
                                wholly new missiles.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The tables<note n="2" xml:id="d114fn2">Attached but not printed is a table,
                        entitled “Soviet and <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Missile Flights,”
                        showing comparative figures in four categories—<gloss target="#t_ICBM1"
                            >ICBM</gloss>s, <gloss target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss>s, operational, and
                            <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss>—for 1968 and 1969.</note> show
                    the figures in more detail.</p>
            </div>
